{"title_page": "Antigius", "text_new": "{{Short description|Butterfly genus in family Lycaenidae}}\n{{Taxobox\n| image = AntigiusButleriFUpUnAC1.jpg\n| image_caption = ''[[Antigius butleri]]''\n| regnum = [[Animal]]ia\n| phylum = [[Arthropod]]a\n| classis = [[Insect]]a\n| ordo = [[Lepidoptera]]\n| familia = [[Lycaenidae]]\n| genus = ''Antigius''\n| genus authority = Sibatani & Ito, 1942\n}}\n'''''Antigius''''' is a genus of [[butterflies]] in the family [[Lycaenidae]]. The species of this genus are found in the eastern [[Palearctic realm]] ([[China]], [[Korea]], [[Japan]], and the [[Russian Far East]]), as well as [[Taiwan]] and [[Myanmar]].\n\n==Species==\n*''[[Antigius attilia]]'' <small>(Bremer, 1861)</small>\n*''[[Antigius butleri]]'' <small>(Fenton, 1881)</small>\n*''[[Antigius cheni]]'' <small>Koiwaya, 2004</small>\n*''[[Antigius jinpingi]]'' <small>Hsu, 2009</small>\n*''[[Antigius shizuyai]]'' <small>Koiwaya, 2002</small>\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.mapress.com/zootaxa/2009/f/zt01983p053.pdf A new species of ''Antigius'' (Lepidoptera: Lycaenidae: Theclini) from Taiwan]\n*[http://ftp.funet.fi/pub/sci/bio/life/insecta/lepidoptera/ditrysia/papilionoidea/lycaenidae/theclinae/antigius/ \"''Antigius'' Sibatani & Ito, 1942\"] at Markku Savela's ''Lepidoptera and Some Other Life Forms''\n*[http://www.boldsystems.org/index.php/Taxbrowser_Taxonpage?taxid=391915 Images representing ''Antigius''] at [[Consortium for the Barcode of Life]]\n{{commonscat|Antigius}}\n{{Wikispecies}}\n\n{{Taxonbar|from=Q1347807}}\n\n[[Category:Theclini]]\n[[Category:Lycaenidae genera]]\n[[Category:Palearctic Lepidoptera]]\n\n\n{{Theclinae-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Short description|Butterfly genus in family Lycaenidae}}\n{{Taxobox\n| image = AntigiusButleriFUpUnAC1.jpg\n| image_caption = ''[[Antigius butleri]]''\n| regnum = [[Animal]]ia\n| phylum = [[Arthropod]]a\n| classis = [[Insect]]a\n| ordo = [[Lepidoptera]]\n| familia = [[Lycaenidae]]\n| genus = ''Antigius''\n| genus authority = Sibatani & Ito, 1942\n}}\n'''''Antigius''''' is a genus of [[butterflies]] in the family [[Lycaenidae]]. The species of this genus are found in the eastern [[Palearctic ream]] ([[China]], [[Korea]], [[Japan]], and the [[Russian Far East]]), as well as [[Taiwan]] and [[Myanmar]].\n\n==Species==\n*''[[Antigius attilia]]'' <small>(Bremer, 1861)</small>\n*''[[Antigius butleri]]'' <small>(Fenton, 1881)</small>\n*''[[Antigius cheni]]'' <small>Koiwaya, 2004</small>\n*''[[Antigius jinpingi]]'' <small>Hsu, 2009</small>\n*''[[Antigius shizuyai]]'' <small>Koiwaya, 2002</small>\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.mapress.com/zootaxa/2009/f/zt01983p053.pdf A new species of ''Antigius'' (Lepidoptera: Lycaenidae: Theclini) from Taiwan]\n*[http://ftp.funet.fi/pub/sci/bio/life/insecta/lepidoptera/ditrysia/papilionoidea/lycaenidae/theclinae/antigius/ \"''Antigius'' Sibatani & Ito, 1942\"] at Markku Savela's ''Lepidoptera and Some Other Life Forms''\n*[http://www.boldsystems.org/index.php/Taxbrowser_Taxonpage?taxid=391915 Images representing ''Antigius''] at [[Consortium for the Barcode of Life]]\n{{commonscat|Antigius}}\n{{Wikispecies}}\n\n{{Taxonbar|from=Q1347807}}\n\n[[Category:Theclini]]\n[[Category:Lycaenidae genera]]\n[[Category:Palearctic Lepidoptera]]\n\n\n{{Theclinae-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Tom Radulovich", "label": "safe", "comment": "fix link", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Antigius"}
{"title_page": "2016 Conference USA Football Championship Game", "text_new": "{{Infobox NCAA football yearly game\n| Game Name          = Conference USA Football Championship Game\n| Title Sponsor      = Dynacraft\n| Optional Subheader = Conference Championship\n| Image              = 2016_Conference_USA_Football_Championship_Game_logo.jpeg\n| Date Game Played   = December 3\n| Year Game Played   = 2016\n| Football Season    = 2016\n| Stadium = [[Houchens Industries\u2013L. T. Smith Stadium]]\n| City = [[Bowling Green, Kentucky]]\n| Visitor School     = Louisiana Tech University\n| Visitor Name Short = Louisiana Tech\n| Visitor Nickname   = Bulldogs\n| Visitor Record     =  8\u20134\n| Visitor AP         = \n| Visitor Coaches    = \n| Visitor CFP        = \n| Visitor Coach      = [[Skip Holtz]]\n| Visitor1           = 17\n| Visitor2           = 10\n| Visitor3           = 14\n| Visitor4           = 3\n| Home School = Western Kentucky University\n| Home Name Short = WKU\n| Home Nickname = Hilltoppers\n| Home Record = 9\u20133\n| Home AP            = \n| Home Coaches       =\n| Home CFP           = \n| Home Coach = [[Jeff Brohm]]\n| Home1              = 24\n| Home2              = 14\n| Home3              = 10\n| Home4              = 10\n| MVP                = RB Anthony Wales (WKU)\n| Odds               = \n| Anthem             =\n| Referee            = Rodney Burnette<ref name=\"Stats\" />\n| Halftime           = \n| Attendance         = 13,213<ref name=\"Stats\">{{cite web|url=http://stats.statbroadcast.com/statmonitr/?id=155318|title=C-USA Championship: Louisiana Tech vs. Western Kentucky|publisher=Stat Broadcast|accessdate=2016-12-03}}</ref>\n| US Network         = [[ESPN]]/[[TuneIn]]\n| US Announcers      = [[Dave Pasch]], [[Tom Luginbill]], [[Quint Kessenich]] (ESPN)<br>[[TJ Rives]], [[Kelly Holcomb]] ([[TuneIn|Tag Sports Group on TuneIn]])\n| Ratings            = \n| Intl Network       = \n| Intl Announcers    = \n}}\n{{2016 Conference USA football standings}}\nThe '''2016 Conference USA Championship Game''' was played on Saturday, December 3, 2016, at [[Houchens Industries\u2013L. T. Smith Stadium]] in [[Bowling Green, Kentucky]], and determined the [[2016 NCAA Division I FBS football season|2016]] [[college football|football]] champion of [[Conference USA]] (C-USA). The game featured the West Division champion [[2016 Louisiana Tech Bulldogs football team|Louisiana Tech]] visiting the East Division champion [[2016 WKU Hilltoppers football team|Western Kentucky Hilltoppers]] (WKU), with the Hilltoppers winning 58\u201344. The game was broadcast nationally by [[ESPN]] for the 5th consecutive year.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fbschedules.com/2016/06/2016-conference-usa-football-tv-schedule-announced/|title=2016 Conference USA Football TV Schedule Announced|work=FBS Schedule}}</ref> The title sponsor was [[Dynacraft BSC]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://conferenceusa.com/news/2016/11/15/FB_1115160037.aspx?path=football|title=C-USA Rolls Out Dynacraft as Football Championship Title Sponsor|publisher=[[Conference USA]]|accessdate=2016-11-15}}</ref>\n\nIf winner of the C-USA Championship Game is one of highest ranked in the [[2016 NCAA Division I FBS football rankings#CFP Rankings|rankings]] of the [[Group of Five conferences|\"Group of Five\" conferences]], the team could be placed in the [[2016\u201317 NCAA football bowl games#College Football Playoff and Championship Game|playoffs]] if not then the [[2017 Cotton Bowl Classic (January)|Cotton Bowl]]. The conference champion if not selected would then pick a bowl game of their choosing to attend that has ties to the conference.\n\nThe 2016 championship game was the 12th game in the championship series. In the [[2015 Conference USA Football Championship Game|2015]] championship game, also hosted by WKU, [[2015 WKU Hilltoppers football team|the Hilltoppers]] defeated [[2015 Southern Miss Golden Eagles football team|Southern Miss]], 45\u201328.\n\nThe game proved to be the last for [[Jeff Brohm]] as WKU's head coach; two days later, he was hired to fill the head coaching vacancy at [[Purdue Boilermakers football|Purdue]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.espn.com/college-football/story/_/id/18209584/purdue-boilermakers-hire-western-kentucky-coach-jeff-brohm |title=Jeff Brohm moving from Western Kentucky to Purdue |publisher=[[ESPN.com]] |date=December 5, 2016 |accessdate=December 5, 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Teams==\n\n===Louisiana Tech===\n{{Main|2016 Louisiana Tech Bulldogs football team}}\nThe Bulldogs got off to a rough start at 1-2 before going into conference play with a close 21\u201320 loss to [[2016 Arkansas Razorbacks football team|Arkansas]]. Louisiana Tech lost its first conference game against [[2016 Middle Tennessee Blue Raiders football team|Middle Tennessee]] in which the Bulldogs lost the game in the last quarter when the Blue Raiders scored 21 points to win 38\u201334. The Bulldogs then went undefeated in conference play before losing their regular-season finale 39\u201324 to [[2016 Southern Miss Golden Eagles football team|Southern Miss]] on November 26. They had already clinched the West Division title on November 12 by defeating [[2016 UTSA Roadrunners football team|UTSA]], winning the division title for the second time in school history.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thenewsstar.com/story/sports/college/louisiana-tech/2016/11/12/tech-wraps-up-c-usa-west-title-seventh-straight-win/93728522/|title=Tech wraps up C-USA West title with seventh straight win|work=The News Star}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.arklatexhomepage.com/sports/la-tech-clinches-west-division-with-63-35-victory|title=LA Tech clinches West Division with 63-35 Victory|work=KTAL}}</ref> The previous time the Bulldogs won the West Division was back in [[2014 Conference USA football season|2014]], which resulted in the Bulldogs [[2014 Conference USA Football Championship Game|losing by 3 points]] to [[2014 Marshall Thundering Herd football team|Marshall]].<ref>{{cite web| url=http://espn.go.com/ncf/boxscore?gameId=400609077 | title=Louisiana Tech Bulldogs vs. Marshall Thundering Herd| publisher=ESPN| date=2014-12-06| accessdate=2016-11-14}}</ref>\n\n===Western Kentucky===\n{{Main|2016 WKU Hilltoppers football team}}\nWKU opened the season with a conference win over [[2016 Rice Owls football team|Rice]], and then went 2\u20132 in its nonconference schedule, with both losses to [[Southeastern Conference]] teams. WKU then resumed its conference schedule at Louisiana Tech, losing 55\u201352, before winning its final six regular-season games, finishing C-USA play as East Division co-champions along with [[2016 Old Dominion Monarchs football team|Old Dominion]]. Both teams finished 7\u20131 in C-USA play, with WKU holding the tiebreaker with a 59\u201324 win over Old Dominion on October 22. Entering the final weekend of conference play, the Hilltoppers could have been beaten out for hosting rights by Louisiana Tech, which entered that weekend 6\u20131 in the conference and held the head-to-head tiebreaker with its win over WKU. However, the Bulldogs lost on November 26 to Southern Miss, leaving them at 6\u20132 in C-USA play. WKU hosted the championship for the second consecutive season, making it the first C-USA school to ever do so.\n\n==Game summary==\nWKU hosted the Bulldogs of Louisiana Tech at [[Houchens Industries\u2013L. T. Smith Stadium]] in [[Bowling Green, Kentucky]] at noon [[Eastern Time Zone|Eastern Time]] on December 3, 2016 and was broadcast on [[ESPN]]. Louisiana Tech held the overall series record over the Hilltoppers 4\u20132 before the matchup. The Bulldogs defeated the Hilltoppers in the last meeting back in the beginning of the season on October 6, 55\u201352.\n\n===Scoring summary===\n{{AmFootballScoreSummaryStart|VisitorName=LATECH|HomeName=WKU|state=}}\n{{AmFootballScoreSummaryEntry\n| Quarter=1\n| Time=11:56\n| Team=WKU\n| DrivePlays=8\n| DriveLength=54\n| DriveTime=3:04\n| Type=FG\n| Kicker=Skyler Simcox\